Difference<L,R>
public static final class Difference.MapDifference<L,R,D> extends Difference<L,R>
It is used to compare two maps and find the common elements, elements only in the left map, elements only in the right map, and elements with different values.

    • of

      public static <CK, K1 extends CK, V1, K2 extends CK, V2> Difference.MapDifference<Map<K1,V1>,Map<K2,V2>,Map<CK,Pair<V1,V2>>> of(Map<? extends K1,? extends V1> map1, Map<? extends K2,? extends V2> map2, BiPredicate<? super V1,? super V2> valueEquivalence) throws IllegalArgumentException
      Compares two maps and finds the common elements, elements only in the left map, elements only in the right map, and elements with different values. It uses a custom value equivalence BiPredicate to determine if two values are considered equal.
      Type Parameters:
      CK - The common key type of the two maps.
      K1 - The key type of the first map.
      V1 - The value type of the first map.
      K2 - The key type of the second map.
      V2 - The value type of the second map.
      Parameters:
      map1 - The first map to be compared.
      map2 - The second map to be compared.
      valueEquivalence - The BiPredicate used to determine if two values are considered equal.
      Returns:
      A MapDifference object containing the common elements, elements only in the left map, elements only in the right map, and elements with different values.
      Throws:
      IllegalArgumentException - If valueEquivalence is null.
      See Also:

    • of

      public static <CK, K1 extends CK, V1, K2 extends CK, V2> Difference.MapDifference<Map<K1,V1>,Map<K2,V2>,Map<CK,Pair<V1,V2>>> of(Map<? extends K1,? extends V1> map1, Map<? extends K2,? extends V2> map2, TriPredicate<? super K1,? super V1,? super V2> valueEquivalence) throws IllegalArgumentException
      Compares two maps and finds the common elements, elements only in the left map, elements only in the right map, and elements with different values. It uses a custom value equivalence BiPredicate to determine if two values are considered equal.
      Type Parameters:
      CK - The common key type of the two maps.
      K1 - The key type of the first map.
      V1 - The value type of the first map.
      K2 - The key type of the second map.
      V2 - The value type of the second map.
      Parameters:
      map1 - The first map to be compared.
      map2 - The second map to be compared.
      valueEquivalence - The TriPredicate used to determine if two values are considered equal. The first parameter of the TriPredicate is the key from the first map, the second and third parameters are the values from the first and second maps respectively.
      Returns:
      A MapDifference object containing the common elements, elements only in the left map, elements only in the right map, and elements with different values.
      Throws:
      IllegalArgumentException - If valueEquivalence is null.
      See Also:

      public static Difference.MapDifference<Map<String,Object>,Map<String,Object>,Map<String,Pair<Object,Object>>> of(Object bean1, Object bean2)
      Compares two beans and finds the common properties, properties only in the first bean, properties only in the second bean, and properties with different values. It uses the Maps.bean2Map method to convert the beans into maps and then compares them.
      Parameters:
      bean1 - The first bean to be compared.
      bean2 - The second bean to be compared.
      Returns:
      A MapDifference object containing the common properties, properties only in the first bean, properties only in the second bean, and properties with different values.
      Throws:
      IllegalArgumentException - If either of the beans is not a bean class.

      public static Difference.MapDifference<Map<String,Object>,Map<String,Object>,Map<String,Pair<Object,Object>>> of(Object bean1, Object bean2, BiPredicate<?,?> valueEquivalence)
      Compares two beans and finds the common properties, properties only in the first bean, properties only in the second bean, and properties with different values. It uses the Maps.bean2Map method to convert the beans into maps and then compares them using a custom value equivalence BiPredicate.
      Parameters:
      bean1 - The first bean to be compared.
      bean2 - The second bean to be compared.
      valueEquivalence - The BiPredicate used to determine if two values are considered equal.
      Returns:

      Throws:
      IllegalArgumentException - If either of the beans is not a bean class, or if valueEquivalence is null.

      public static Difference.MapDifference<Map<String,Object>,Map<String,Object>,Map<String,Pair<Object,Object>>> of(Object bean1, Object bean2, TriPredicate<String,?,?> valueEquivalence)
      Compares two beans and finds the common properties, properties only in the first bean, properties only in the second bean, and properties with different values. It uses the Maps.bean2Map method to convert the beans into maps and then compares them using a custom value equivalence BiPredicate.
      Parameters:
      bean1 - The first bean to be compared.
      bean2 - The second bean to be compared.
      valueEquivalence - The TriPredicate used to determine if two values are considered equal. The first parameter of the TriPredicate is the property name, the second and third parameters are the property values from the first and second beans respectively.
      Returns:
      A MapDifference object containing the common properties, properties only in the first bean, properties only in the second bean, and properties with different values.
      Throws:
      IllegalArgumentException - If either of the beans is not a bean class, or if valueEquivalence is null.
